⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Question 61/120 – Latest Record Per Customer

🎤 Interview Question

You are given a customer transaction DataFrame.

Write PySpark code to display only the latest transaction for each customer based on transaction_date.


---

📊 Input Dataset

customer_id	transaction_id	transaction_date	amount

101	T1	2024-01-10	1000
101	T2	2024-03-15	1500
102	T3	2024-02-20	2000
102	T4	2024-01-18	1800
103	T5	2024-04-01	2500



---

✅ Expected Output

customer_id	transaction_id	transaction_date	amount

101	T2	2024-03-15	1500
102	T3	2024-02-20	2000
103	T5	2024-04-01	2500



---

✅ Recommended Solution

from pyspark.sql.window import Window
from pyspark.sql.functions import row_number, col

window_spec = (
    Window.partitionBy("customer_id")
          .orderBy(col("transaction_date").desc())
)

result = (
    df.withColumn("rn", row_number().over(window_spec))
      .filter(col("rn") == 1)
      .drop("rn")
)

result.show()


---

🎤 Most Asked Interview Questions

Q1. Why use row_number() instead of rank()?

Answer

row_number() guarantees exactly one latest record per customer.

If two records have the same date:

rank() returns multiple rows with rank = 1.

row_number() returns only one row.



---

Q2. What if two transactions have the same transaction_date?

Answer

Use a secondary sort column.

Example:

.orderBy(
    col("transaction_date").desc(),
    col("transaction_id").desc()
)

This ensures deterministic results.


---

Q3. Where is this pattern used?

Answer

Latest customer record

Latest employee salary

Latest product price

Latest order status

Latest account balance



